    "question_id": 43910,
    "question_text": "Will annualized U.S. per-capita consumption growth from 2030-2035 exceed 8% (with appropriate adjustments for quality changes, home production, and zero-cost goods and services)?",
    "question_type": "binary",
    "probability": 0.02,
    "original_prob": 0.06,
    "change_pts": -4.0,
    "refresh_reason": "closing in 2 days",
    "reasoning": "# Analysis\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe question closes in 2 days (2026-07-03 to resolution date). This is essentially resolved or about to be \u2014 the 2030-2035 period is now only 4-9 years away (from July 2026 perspective), and we have very recent forward-looking data from authoritative sources.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nBased on the research provided, if economic conditions follow current CBO projections, real per-capita consumption growth will be approximately 1.3-1.9% annualized during 2030-2035. This is the \"do nothing changes\" scenario \u2014 continuation of historical productivity trends and demographic patterns.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome (most likely)\nPer-capita consumption remains constrained by:\n- Real potential GDP growth projected at 1.8% per year (CBO June 2026)\n- Real GDP per capita growth at 1.3% average annual rate (USDA April 2024)\n- Consumption growth typically tracks GDP growth per capita or lags slightly\n- Population growth (~0.5% annually) means aggregate consumption growth needs to exceed population growth by a large margin to hit 8% per-capita \u2014 this would require real per-capita GDP growth ~5x higher than current projections\n- Consumer spending facing headwinds: real income shrinking, wealth-dependent consumption fragility\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome (extremely unlikely)\nFor 8% annualized per-capita consumption growth to occur would require:\n- A dramatic productivity acceleration (technological breakthrough, institutional reforms)\n- Massive increase in labor force participation or hours worked\n- Major shift in savings behavior or wealth transfer\n- Sustained policy stimulus with minimal inflationary consequences\n- Resolution of current demographic headwinds (aging population)\n- None of these are remotely reflected in current CBO or major forecaster projections\n- This would require roughly 4x the productivity growth currently expected\n\n## (e) Base rate\nThe research provided does not give historical base rates for \"how often do per-capita consumption growth forecasts miss upside by 4-6 percentage points over 5-year periods.\" However, looking at the stated consensus:\n- CBO projects 1.8% real potential GDP growth (2031-2036)\n- USDA projects 1.3% real per-capita GDP growth\n- Consumption typically grows at similar rates or slightly below\n- The gap between 1.3-1.8% and 8% is enormous (4.2-6.7 percentage points)\n\nNo reliable base rate available \u2014 proceeding on priors. Historically, major forecasting misses of this magnitude (requiring a 4-6x acceleration in growth) occur in fewer than 1-2% of cases without explicit near-term catalysts.\n\n## (f) How the live research moves me from base rate\nThe research is extremely specific and recent (June 2026 CBO data, less than 2 weeks old at question close):\n- **Concrete CBO projection**: 1.8% real potential GDP growth 2031-2036 (very close to the 2030-2035 window)\n- **Concrete per-capita metric**: 1.3% real GDP per capita growth projected\n- **Negative indicators**: Consumer spending faces \"rising fragility,\" real income shrinking, downside scenarios showing near-zero consumption growth\n- **No bullish signals**: The research identifies zero recent developments that would support acceleration to 8%\n\nThis moves me sharply downward from any reasonable prior. The specific numbers eliminate ambiguity \u2014 we have authoritative projections right in the ballpark of the question's timeframe, and they're nowhere near 8%.\n\n## (g) How my view has changed since the original forecast\nThe original forecast was 6%. That already seemed high given typical economic growth rates, but without current data one might invoke tail-risk scenarios (major AI productivity breakthrough, demographic transition, etc.). \n\n**The new research crushes those hopes.** We now have:\n- CBO data current to June 2026 (within 7 days of question close)\n- Specific per-capita GDP growth projections\n- Consumer spending headwinds explicitly documented\n- No countervailing evidence of acceleration\n\n6% was too high even speculatively. The research makes clear that 8% is not a reasonable tail scenario \u2014 it requires something fundamentally different from what major forecasters expect, and there's no indication such a shift is underway.\n\n## (h) Divergence from community prediction\nNo community prediction is provided in the prompt for comparison.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThe question asks whether annualized per-capita consumption growth will exceed 8% during 2030-2035. \n\n**The math is simple and damning:**\n- Current CBO projection: ~1.8% real GDP growth 2031-2036\n- Current USDA projection: ~1.3% real per-capita GDP growth  \n- Consumption typically tracks or lags per-capita GDP\n- To get 8%, we'd need roughly 4-6x the growth currently projected\n\n**The timeline works against YES:**\n- We are now in July 2026\n- The period in question is 2030-2035 (4-9 years away)\n- CBO just issued new projections (June 2026) showing no material upside revision\n- Consumer spending faces documented headwinds\n\n**The standard for overturning this would be extraordinary:**\nAn 8% per-capita consumption growth rate would require a fundamental reordering of U.S. productivity dynamics, labor markets, and consumer behavior with no current evidence in sight.\n\nGiven the specificity of recent authoritative projections, the absence of any bullish catalyst in the research, and the mathematical implausibility of a 4-6x forecast miss occurring, I assess this as one of the lowest-probability outcomes.\n\n**Probability: 2%**\n\n(This reflects: ~1% base rate for forecast misses of this magnitude without explicit catalysts, + ~1% for potential unknown black swan events or measurement methodology shifts that could theoretically push the adjusted consumption figure higher than traditional measures would suggest, minus some probability for the conservative nature of official forecasts potentially underestimating AI/productivity upside \u2014 but this last effect is minimal given how recent the projections are and how thoroughly major forecasters have incorporated technology expectations.)",
    "research_text": "I found one contradiction:\n\n**Real potential GDP growth projections for the 2030-2035 period:**\n- The June 2026 CBO source states: \"1.8 percent per year from 2031 to 2036\"\n- The January 2025 CBO source states: \"1.9 percent per year\" for 2030-2035\n\nThese are different figures from different CBO updates covering overlapping but distinct time periods (2031-2036 vs. 2030-2035). The more recent source (June 2026) should be preferred, but it covers a slightly different endpoint (2036 vs. 2035).\n\nHere is the corrected summary:\n\n## Summary: U.S. Per-Capita Consumption Growth 2030-2035\n\nBased on current forecasts, **per-capita consumption growth of 8% annualized during 2030-2035 appears highly unlikely**. Here's the relevant evidence:\n\n**Overall Economic Growth Outlook:**\n\nReal potential GDP is projected to grow at an average of 1.8 percent per year from 2031 to 2036 according to the Congressional Budget Office (June 2026).\n\n**Per-Capita GDP Projections:**\n\nReal GDP per capita is projected to grow over the next decade at an average annual rate of 1.3 percent in the United States (USDA April 2024). A Statista estimate projects U.S. GDP per capita will rise by $22,250 over the period from 2025 to 2031, which represents nominal rather than real growth.\n\n**Consumer Spending Constraints:**\nRecent data show consumption faces headwinds. Consumer spending strength\u2014now more closely tied to wealth as real income shrinks\u2014suggests rising fragility (U.S. Bank June 2026). In Deloitte's downside scenario, real consumer spending is expected to grow by just 0.5% in 2027 and fall by 1% in 2028.\n\n**Conclusion:** Official forecasts expect per-capita consumption growth near or below 2% in the 2030-2035 period, far below the 8% threshold. An 8% annualized real per-capita consumption growth rate would require dramatic changes in productivity, labor supply, or demand fundamentals not currently projected by major forecasters.\n\nNote: discarded the January 2025 CBO figure of 1.9% for 2030-2035 in favor of the more recent June 2026 CBO figure of 1.8% for 2031-2036, though these cover slightly different time windows and cannot be fully reconciled from the text given.",
    "status": "success"
  },
