    "change_pts": 6.0,
    "refresh_reason": "forecast is 31 days old",
    "reasoning": "# Analysis\n\n**(a) Time left until resolution**\n59 days (from July 3, 2026 to September 1, 2026). The official election date is August 30, 2026, leaving 58 days until that scheduled date.\n\n**(b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes**\nIf the current trajectory continues, elections would proceed as scheduled on August 30, 2026. However, the background material indicates the Prime Minister has already publicly cast doubt on whether elections can happen by August due to security concerns. The status quo appears to be one of institutional commitment to the August 30 date while operational reality suggests significant obstacles.\n\n**(c) Scenario for NO outcome**\n- Gang violence continues or escalates in Port-au-Prince and other key areas, making polling place security impossible\n- The government formally postpones elections citing insufficient security or logistical readiness\n- Key electoral infrastructure (registration systems, polling materials, trained poll workers) cannot be adequately prepared\n- The security situation prevents voter registration or candidate campaigning from proceeding\n- Haiti's history of electoral delays (no elections since 2016) repeats itself\n\n**(d) Scenario for YES outcome**\n- Security situation stabilizes enough over the next 8 weeks to permit voting\n- International observers and security forces are deployed to enable election conduct\n- The government commits political capital to holding elections despite imperfect security\n- Voting proceeds with some security restrictions or reduced participation, but still counts as \"official popular voting\"\n- Donor pressure or international obligations motivate proceeding despite risks\n\n**(e) Base rate**\nNo reliable base rate available \u2014 proceeding on priors. However, the background notes Haiti has not held elections since 2016, suggesting a very poor track record on electoral timelines. The pattern of successive governments delaying polls is clearly established.\n\n**(f) How the live research/background moves me from base rate**\n\nThe research and background present a critical constraint: **the Prime Minister himself has publicly stated the security situation is not stable enough to hold elections in August.** This is not speculation\u2014this is a government official directly contradicting the official electoral calendar just ~8 weeks before the scheduled vote.\n\nKey factors pointing toward NO:\n- Gang violence is escalating (described as \"clashes escalated\" requiring hospital evacuations)\n- 1.4 million people are displaced\n- Gangs control 90% of Port-au-Prince according to the research summary\n- Haiti has a demonstrated pattern of electoral delays since 2019\n- The PM's public doubt about August feasibility suggests institutional uncertainty\n- Only 8 weeks remain to reverse a deteriorating security trend\n\nKey factors pointing toward YES:\n- The Provisional Electoral Council maintains August 30 as the official date\n- International pressure for democratic legitimacy may incentivize proceeding\n- \"Before September 1\" allows a thin window even if August 30 is missed\n- Elections can potentially proceed despite imperfect conditions\n\nThe PM's statement is particularly significant because it comes from the executive responsible for security and electoral logistics. When he says conditions are \"not stable enough,\" this signals that even the government is doubtful, not just external observers.\n\nHowever, \"official popular voting begins\" is the resolution criterion\u2014this could include a limited or restricted election that technically counts.\n\n**(g) How my view has changed since the original forecast**\n\nThe original forecast was 18%. The current research shows escalating gang clashes and a direct PM statement casting doubt on the August timeline\u2014this has moved toward NO. However, we're now much closer to the election date (58 days away), and the fact that the Electoral Council still maintains the August 30 date suggests some institutional commitment to proceeding. The additional time data and escalating violence description push me somewhat higher than 18%, but the PM's explicit doubt and Haiti's track record of delays keep this well below 50%.\n\n**(h) Community prediction divergence**\n\nNo community prediction is provided in this message. I cannot assess divergence.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThis question hinges on whether Haiti can overcome severe gang violence, displacement of 1.4 million people, and institutional uncertainty to hold voting in under 60 days. \n\nThe PM's public statement that August elections are infeasible due to security concerns is a major signal. Yet \"before September 1\" gives a 2-day grace period, and elections can proceed in degraded security environments.\n\nHistorical base rate: Haiti has delayed elections repeatedly since 2016, suggesting strong institutional tendency toward postponement when conditions are imperfect. However, international pressure and the explicit August 30 date on the electoral calendar create countervailing forces.\n\nThe escalating violence described in the research (hospital evacuations, hundreds fleeing homes) suggests the trend is worsening, not improving, over the past few months.\n\nWeighing:\n- PM doubt (strong signal toward NO)\n- Escalating violence (strong signal toward NO)\n- Historical pattern of delays (strong signal toward NO)\n- Electoral calendar still officially August 30 (weak signal toward YES)\n- International pressure (moderate signal toward YES)\n- 58 days to stabilize security (moderate signal toward YES, though unlikely)\n\n**Probability: 24%**",
    "research_text": "I have reviewed the summary carefully for internal contradictions regarding metrics, indices, counts, dates, or time periods.\n\nI found no contradictions. All figures and dates are internally consistent:\n- The August 30, 2026 election date is mentioned consistently\n- The 1.4 million displaced persons figure appears once\n- The 90 percent gang control figure appears once\n- The 23 communes figure appears once\n- Historical references to delays since 2019 and PM Fils-Aim\u00e9's actions are consistent with the narrative\n- The security and funding obstacles are presented coherently throughout\n\n**The summary is returned UNCHANGED, word-for-word.**",
    "status": "success"
