    "reasoning": "# Analysis\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\n~8.9 years (from July 3, 2026 to end of 2035). This is a long-horizon question with meaningful uncertainty.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe employment-population ratio for ages 25-54 is currently 80.7% (April 2026, per background). If demographic and labor market trends continue on their current trajectory, the ratio would likely remain elevated. Historical stability suggests ratios in the high 70s to low 80s are typical for this prime working-age cohort during normal economic conditions. Under a status quo scenario, the ratio would likely remain above 70%.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome (ratio stays \u226570%)\n- Continued economic growth and stable labor demand\n- Immigration sustaining workforce growth\n- No major recession or structural economic disruption\n- Demographic trends in aging proceeding slowly enough that prime-age employment remains robust\n- Potential policy responses (e.g., raising retirement age, labor market reforms) supporting employment\n- This aligns with the long-term historical pattern where 70% is only breached during crises\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome (ratio falls below 70%)\n- Severe and sustained recession or depression lasting years\n- Structural shift in labor force participation among ages 25-54 (e.g., mass early retirement, reduced workforce participation)\n- Major demographic collapse or emigration\n- Permanent loss of employment demand (technological displacement, offshoring, deindustrialization)\n- Long-term wage stagnation forcing workers out of labor force\n- Policy changes that discourage or prevent employment in this age group\n\n## (e) Base rate\nThe background indicates that 70% was last achieved during COVID and before that in the late 1970s. This suggests the ratio falls below 70% only during major economic crises or severe structural recessions\u2014rare events with a frequency roughly once per 40+ years historically. Over a 9-year horizon with no current crisis indicated, the base rate for such a decline should be low.\n\n## (f) How current information moves me from base rate\n\n**Current data (from research summary):**\n- Employment-population ratio is 80.7% as of April 2026\n- Labor force participation rate is projected to decline from 62.6% (2024) to 61.1% (2034)\n- These are moderate downward trends, not cliff-like declines\n\n**Key implications:**\n- Current ratio is 10.7 percentage points above the 70% threshold\n- The projected labor participation decline is modest (~1.5 percentage points over 10 years)\n- No imminent crisis is indicated; the economy appears stable\n- The decline trajectory shown is gradual, not accelerating toward a 70% breach\n\nThe research suggests secular headwinds (aging, lower participation) but at a glacial pace insufficient to breach 70% in the next 9 years absent a major shock.\n\n## (g) How my view has changed (or not) since the original forecast\nThe previous forecast was 22%. Given:\n- The current ratio is still elevated at 80.7%\n- No crisis is evident in the data\n- Projected declines are modest and gradual\n- 9 years is enough time for major shocks, but not enough for slow demographic trends alone to drop the ratio 10+ points\n\nI find 22% somewhat reasonable but possibly slightly generous to the YES scenario. The steady-state scenario heavily favors staying above 70%. I would expect a forecast in the 15-25% range to be appropriately calibrated, reflecting that this requires either an unexpected severe crisis or a structural shift not yet evident in the data.\n\n## (h) Community prediction\nNo community prediction was provided in the prompt. I cannot compare to or explain divergence from a current Metaculus forecast.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\n**For a fall below 70% by 2035, one of these must occur:**\n1. A major recession/depression in the 2026-2035 window (severe enough to trigger sustained 10-point employment decline)\n2. Structural labor force exit among prime-age workers (e.g., policy shift, pension changes, disability expansion)\n3. Combination of slow demographic decline + economic weakness\n\n**Against:**\n- Current ratio is 80.7%, providing a 10.7-point buffer\n- No crisis visible; labor market appears stable\n- Projected participation decline (~1.5 points) is modest\n- Historical precedent shows 70% breached only in severe crises (COVID, late 1970s stagflation)\n- 9-year horizon is meaningful but not long enough for gradual trends alone\n\n**Tail risks:**\n- Unforeseen geopolitical/economic shock (financial crisis, war, pandemic sequel)\n- Policy changes (e.g., mass retirement incentives, immigration restrictions reducing workforce)\n- Technological disruption causing sustained prime-age unemployment\n\nGiven the substantial buffer, stable current conditions, and modest projected secular declines, I assess the probability as somewhat low but not negligible given tail risks and the long time horizon.\n\n**Probability: 20%**",
    "research_text": "I've reviewed the summary carefully for internal contradictions regarding the same metrics across different dates or time periods.\n\n**Finding:** No internal contradictions detected.\n\nThe summary references:\n- Employment-population ratio for ages 25-54: 80.7% as of February 2026 (single data point, no conflicting figure)\n- Labor force participation rate decline: 62.6% in 2024 to 61.1% by 2034 (consistent downward trend, no contradictory values)\n- Overall demographic trends and projections are consistent throughout\n\nThe summary is returned **UNCHANGED, word-for-word**.",
