    "reasoning": "(a) **Time left until resolution:**\nToday is July 3, 2026. The resolution window is May 4, 2026 to September 1, 2026.\n- Time elapsed in window: ~29 days\n- Time remaining in window: ~60 days (approximately 2 months)\n\n(b) **Status quo outcome if nothing changes:**\nNo successful coup occurs. The current political structures in Africa and Latin America remain in place. This is the baseline expectation for most countries most of the time.\n\n(c) **Scenario for NO outcome:**\nPolitical tensions remain elevated in various countries (particularly in Sahel region, Venezuela, Peru, Bolivia) but do not crystallize into successful coups. Military attempts are suppressed, institutional checks hold, or attempted coups fail to consolidate control over both government and military apparatus.\n\n(d) **Scenario for YES outcome:**\nA military or elite faction successfully executes a coup d'\u00e9tat in Africa (most likely Sahel region given recent pattern) or Latin America, establishing firm control over government and military within the timeframe, with organized resistance ceasing per the definition.\n\n(e) **Base rate:**\nThe background material provides historical context showing:\n- Africa: Approximately 2-3 successful coups per year in recent years (Guinea-Bisau Nov 2025, Madagascar Oct 2025, Mali 2020-2021, Niger 2023, Gabon 2023, Burkina Faso 2022 twice, Guinea 2021). That's roughly 8 coups in ~5 years = ~1.6 per year on average.\n- Latin America: Far fewer successful coups\u2014the examples given are mostly failed attempts (Peru self-coup attempt 2022, Brazil Congress attack 2023, Bolivia coup attempt 2024). Last successful Latin American coup was considerably earlier.\n\nBase rate for 2-month window in Africa: Given ~1-2 successful coups per year, probability in any 2-month window (1/6 of a year) would be roughly 17-33% if uniform distribution.\n\nBase rate for 2-month window in Latin America: Much lower, perhaps 1-5% given rarity of successful coups in the region recently.\n\n(f) **How the live research/data moves me from base rate:**\n\nThe CURRENT RESEARCH block provides critical information:\n- **Benin**: Forecast probability cited as 75% for Africa (implicitly Benin appears to be a major focus given the 75% figure for Africa)\n- **Guinea-Bissau**: Late 2025 tensions mentioned\n- **Burkina Faso**: January 7, 2026 military court martial date mentioned\n- **Nigeria**: May 2026 court martial mentioned\n- **Venezuela**: January 3, 2026 reference (political instability context)\n\nThe research indicates several countries have elevated coup risk. Benin appears to be a particularly acute concern (the 75% figure for Africa suggests concentrated risk). However, the research also indicates these are forecasts/projections, not certainties.\n\nThe timeframe is now only 60 days remaining (July 3 to September 1, 2026). We are approaching the end of the resolution window, and no successful coup has yet occurred in the specified window (May 4 onwards).\n\n**Critical consideration**: The question asks specifically for coups occurring \"after May 4, 2026 and before September 1, 2026.\" We are now almost halfway through this window (29 of 120 days elapsed). The absence of a coup in the first month\u2014during a period with elevated tensions in Benin, Burkina Faso, and other Sahel countries\u2014suggests either:\n1. Risk was overestimated by forecasters\n2. Coup attempts were suppressed or did not materialize as predicted\n3. Risk remains concentrated in final 2 months\n\n(g) **How my view has changed from the original 18% forecast:**\n\nThe original forecast of 18% appears to have been too low given:\n- Extremely elevated coup activity in Africa (11 coups/attempts listed from 2020-2025)\n- Specific intelligence suggesting Benin at 75% risk\n- Multiple Sahel countries with military tensions\n\nHowever, the fact that we're now 29 days into the resolution window with no successful coup, combined with the research indicating these were forecasts rather than imminent events, suggests the middle-range probability is more appropriate than the original 18%.\n\nThe previous forecast of 18% likely underweighted African risk but may have been more realistic about the 2-month window than the 75% Benin figure suggests. The gap between high regional risk and actual coup materialization in a specific 2-month window is significant.\n\n(h) **Community prediction divergence:**\nNo explicit current community prediction is provided in the message for this specific question timeframe. The \"31 days old\" refresh note indicates the previous forecast was 18%, but this appears to be individual forecast data, not aggregated community prediction.\n\n---\n\n**REASONING ON FINAL PROBABILITY:**\n\n1. **Base rates favor YES**: ~17-33% for Africa alone in a 2-month window given historical frequency, plus 1-5% for Latin America = roughly 20-38% combined base rate.\n\n2. **Specific risk factors favor YES**: \n   - Benin cited at 75% risk (though timeframe unclear)\n   - Multiple Sahel countries in turbulent political situations\n   - Historical pattern shows clustering of coups in the region\n\n3. **Factors favoring NO**:\n   - 29 days have passed in the window with no successful coup despite elevated tensions\n   - Forecasts of risk don't always materialize\n   - Military coup attempts increasingly face international pushback\n   - 60 days remaining is still relatively narrow timeframe\n\n4. **Reconciling the contradiction**:\n   The 75% figure for Benin likely refers to a longer timeframe or higher probability of attempted coups rather than successful establishment of control. The Powell & Thyne definition requires both government AND military control with organized resistance ceasing\u2014a high bar.\n\n5. **Recency adjustment**:\n   The fact that we've passed through the first month without a successful coup, during supposedly high-risk period, suggests either risk was overstated or attempts are being forestalled. This warrants modest downward adjustment from base rate but not dramatic.\n\n**Final calibration:**\n- Base rate (Africa + Latin America): ~25%\n- Adjustment for 29 days passing without coup: -5% to -8%\n- Adjustment for specific risk concentration in Benin/Burkina Faso: +3% to +5%\n- Adjustment for institutional resistance and international pressure: -2%\n\nThis yields approximately: 18-23% range.\n\nGiven the original forecast was 18% and specific intelligence about Benin at elevated risk, but also acknowledging the passage of time without materialization, I estimate:\n\n**Probability: 24%**",
    "research_text": "I found no internal contradictions in this summary. All dates, figures, and attributions are consistent throughout:\n\n- The May 2026 forecast probability figures (75% for Africa, 15% for Latin America) are cited once each\n- Specific events are dated consistently (December 7, 2025 for Benin; late 2025 for both Benin and Guinea-Bissau; January 7, 2026 for Burkina Faso; January 3, 2026 for Venezuela; May 2026 for Nigeria court martial)\n- No metrics are assigned different values across different time periods\n\nThe summary is returned UNCHANGED, word-for-word.",
