event\n- Major international competitions are rarely relocated this close to the scheduled date\n- There is no indication in the research of any plans to change the location\n\n(g) **How my view has changed since the original forecast:**\nThe original forecast was 15% probability of a China location. That forecast likely predated the official announcement of Dubai as the host city. Now that the location is officially confirmed as Dubai (per the research provided), the probability should shift dramatically downward. The 15% estimate would have been based on uncertainty about where the 2026 event would be held. That uncertainty has been resolved by the official announcement.\n\n(h) **Community prediction:**\nNo current community prediction is provided in this message, so I cannot compare or explain divergence.\n\n---\n\n**REASONING SUMMARY:**\n\nThe critical fact here is that the ICPC has officially announced Dubai, U.A.E. as the host city for the 2026 World Finals. This is not a rumor, speculation, or preliminary plan\u2014it is the official determination. With approximately 4-5 months until the scheduled November 2026 event, relocating to an entirely different country (China) would be unprecedented disruption for a major international programming competition.\n\nThe only scenarios where this resolves \"Yes\" would involve:\n1. A catastrophic unforeseen event forcing emergency relocation to China\n2. The research information being incorrect or outdated\n3. An extraordinary last-minute organizational decision\n\nEach of these is extremely unlikely given:\n- We are in mid-2026, very close to the event date\n- The official announcement is clear\n- There is no indication of problems or contingency planning\n- International sporting/academic events rarely relocate this late\n\nThe previous 15% forecast was likely made when the location was still undecided. Now that it is decided (and not China), the probability should reflect the extremely low likelihood of a change.\n\n**Probability: 2%**\n\n(The 2% rather than 0% accounts for the small tail risk of unforeseen circumstances forcing an emergency relocation, but this is a minimal probability given how late in the planning cycle we are and how definitively the location has been announced.)",
